        {
            "id": "435d759bfed749ada0ad5",
            "questionText": "A blacksmith heats a $!$0.5 \\; kg$!$ metal horseshoe in a forge. The horseshoe, initially at room temperature ($!$25^{\\circ}C$!$), is plunged into a $!$5 \\; kg$!$ water bath (initially at $!$20^{\\circ}C$!$) for quenching. Assuming the specific heat capacity of the metal is $!$450 \\; J/kg \\cdot K$!$ and the specific heat capacity of water is $!$4186 \\; J/kg \\cdot K$!$, and that the horseshoe is heated to $!$800^{\\circ}C$!$ before being plunged into water, calculate the final temperature of the water and horseshoe after thermal equilibrium is achieved. Neglect heat losses to the surroundings.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "80f359a2882f4e5785505",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula used to calculate the amount of heat transferred when the temperature changes. Which of the following formulas correctly represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3ed6a9b8-e10e-4b9d-8aee-d243dc6ee1d9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = mc\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = m\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = c\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "70d211f3fe2744dcae29a",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the heat transfer formula, calculate the product of the mass and specific heat capacity for the metal horseshoe. Multiply its mass ($!$0.5\\;kg$!$) by its specific heat capacity ($!$450\\;J/kg\\cdot K$!$). What value do you get?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "225"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J/K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "9414abbf-4451-4fb2-8108-34d36766c93b"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "c0567a649cf8408e89957",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Next, compute the product of the mass and specific heat capacity for the water bath. Multiply the mass of water ($!$5\\;kg$!$) by its specific heat capacity ($!$4186\\;J/kg\\cdot K$!$). What result do you obtain?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "20930"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J/K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "9414abbf-4451-4fb2-8108-34d36766c93b"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "b3c8dc2db4ac4ad78ee0a",
                    "stepText": "Now, set up the energy conservation equation. The heat lost by the metal equals the heat gained by the water, which can be expressed as: $!$225(800-T_f)=20930(T_f-20)$!$. Solve this equation for $!$T_f$!$ to find the final equilibrium temperature.",
